      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>LinkedIn Company Page</strong> is a free business profile on LinkedIn representing a company or organisation. It serves as the brand's official hub for company updates, job listings, and professional content. For B2B businesses, a well-maintained Company Page is essential — prospects research vendors on LinkedIn before purchasing, job seekers evaluate culture before applying, and partners assess credibility through your page before engaging.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Cost</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Free to create</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media / B2B</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Weekly posting follower growth</div>
            <div class="tms-value">5.6x vs monthly</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">LinkedIn is where B2B buying decisions happen. The typical B2B buyer checks a vendor's LinkedIn Company Page before a sales call. An incomplete, stale, or absent page signals one thing: the company does not take its professional presence seriously. In a market where 80% of B2B leads originate from LinkedIn, that is a signal worth fixing.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a LinkedIn Company Page?</h2>
        <p>A LinkedIn Company Page is a verified business profile on LinkedIn — distinct from individual member profiles — that represents a company, non-profit, educational institution, or other organisation. It is created and managed by designated administrators (typically marketing or HR teams) and is publicly visible to all LinkedIn members and to general search engines.</p>
        <p>The page includes:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Company overview:</strong> Name, logo, banner image, tagline, website URL, industry, company size, and headquarters</li>
          <li><strong>About section:</strong> Up to 2,000 characters describing the company, its specialties, and its mission</li>
          <li><strong>Posts feed:</strong> Company updates, articles, shared content, and native formats (polls, documents, videos)</li>
          <li><strong>Jobs tab:</strong> Current open positions, integrated with LinkedIn's job search</li>
          <li><strong>People tab:</strong> Employees with LinkedIn profiles who list the company as their employer</li>
          <li><strong>Analytics:</strong> Follower demographics, post reach, engagement rates, and visitor statistics</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why completeness matters</div>
          <p>LinkedIn's own data shows <strong>Company Pages with complete information get 30% more weekly views</strong> than incomplete profiles. Completeness signals are factored into LinkedIn's internal search algorithm — a fully filled-out page with active posting ranks higher in LinkedIn search results for your company name and industry keywords.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why a LinkedIn Company Page matters for B2B businesses</h2>
        <p>LinkedIn is where B2B buying decisions are researched and validated. Four reasons the Company Page is not optional for B2B brands:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Professional credibility and first impressions.</strong> A prospect who has just heard your brand name for the first time will check your LinkedIn before your website. An incomplete or abandoned page — or no page at all — raises an immediate credibility flag. A polished, active page is a trust signal that no other social platform provides for B2B audiences.</li>
          <li><strong>Content distribution through follower feeds and employee networks.</strong> Every post on a Company Page reaches followers' feeds. When employees share or comment on company posts, the reach multiplies exponentially through their personal networks. LinkedIn data shows employee networks are 10x the size of a company's follower base on average.</li>
          <li><strong>Lead generation through follower conversion.</strong> LinkedIn research shows <strong>followers are twice as likely to convert to a customer</strong> as non-followers. The Company Page is the organic mechanism for accumulating that high-intent audience.</li>
          <li><strong>Talent attraction.</strong> 87% of candidates check a company's LinkedIn presence before applying. A page with active culture content, employee spotlights, and a populated job listings tab attracts better applicants and reduces recruiter costs.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to set up and grow a LinkedIn Company Page</h2>
        <p>Effective Company Page management has three components: setup, content strategy, and analytics-driven iteration.</p>

        <h3>Setup and optimisation</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Create the page via linkedin.com/company/setup — you need a personal LinkedIn account as the admin</li>
          <li>Add company name, logo (300x300px minimum), and banner image (1128x191px) — visual completeness is the first thing visitors assess</li>
          <li>Write a compelling "About" section using keywords prospects would use to search for your category</li>
          <li>Fill in all fields: industry, company size, website URL, specialties (up to 20), and founding year</li>
          <li>Add a custom button with a relevant CTA: "Visit website", "Contact us", or "Learn more"</li>
          <li>Claim your custom URL: linkedin.com/company/yourcompanyname</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Content strategy</h3>
        <p>Consistent, varied content is the primary driver of follower growth and engagement. LinkedIn recommends a mix:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Company news and milestones:</strong> Product launches, funding announcements, awards — validates the brand's momentum</li>
          <li><strong>Industry insights and thought leadership:</strong> Curated external articles with original perspective, or original point-of-view posts — builds authority</li>
          <li><strong>Employee spotlights:</strong> Profiles of team members and their work — highest engagement rate of any content type on Company Pages</li>
          <li><strong>Native documents:</strong> Uploaded PDFs/presentations (carousels) — LinkedIn's algorithm favours native document uploads over external links</li>
          <li><strong>Polls:</strong> Quick audience research that drives engagement spikes — comments on polls generate additional algorithmic reach</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Optimal cadence: 3-5 posts per week. LinkedIn data shows <strong>companies posting weekly see 5.6x more follower growth</strong> than those posting monthly.</p>

        <h3>Analytics and growth</h3>
        <p>LinkedIn Page Analytics provides data on impressions, clicks, engagement rate, follower demographics (job function, seniority, industry), and visitor behaviour. Use this to:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Identify which content formats and topics drive the most engagement</li>
          <li>Understand the seniority and function breakdown of your followers (validates ICP targeting)</li>
          <li>Track follower growth rate and identify which posts drove spikes</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Content types ranked by organic reach on Company Pages</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Content type</th><th>Relative reach</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
            </thead>
