        <h2 id="examples">Real LinkedIn Company Page examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — IT consulting firm growing from 800 to 6,000 followers</h3>
        <p>An IT consulting firm with 800 followers committed to 4 posts per week — alternating between thought leadership articles, case study summaries, team spotlights, and industry news commentary. They encouraged all 45 employees to follow the page and reshare posts weekly. In 8 months, the page grew to 6,000 followers. Inbound demo requests attributed to LinkedIn increased from 2 per month to 11 per month over the same period.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — accounting firm using LinkedIn newsletter for client retention</h3>
        <p>An accounting firm published a bi-weekly LinkedIn newsletter — "Tax Intelligence Weekly" — covering regulatory changes and tax planning strategies for SMBs. The newsletter reached 3,200 subscribers within 6 months (2x their email list size). The firm attributed 25% of new business in Q1 to leads who mentioned the newsletter as their first touchpoint with the brand.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">LinkedIn Company Page vs personal profile — how they work together</h2>
        <p>Most B2B brands underuse their Company Page by treating it as a standalone channel. The highest-performing LinkedIn strategies integrate the Company Page with employees' personal profiles.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>LinkedIn Company Page</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Official brand voice — permanent and searchable</li>
              <li>Hub for job postings, product news, and company content</li>
              <li>Analytics on follower demographics and post performance</li>
              <li>Can run LinkedIn Ads from the page</li>
              <li>Lower organic reach than personal profiles</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Employee personal profiles</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Human voices — typically 3-10x the organic reach of Company Pages</li>
              <li>Build individual expertise and trust with prospects</li>
              <li>Resharing company content amplifies it to personal networks</li>
              <li>No LinkedIn Ads capability</li>
              <li>Owned by the employee, not the company</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for LinkedIn Company Pages</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Complete every field before your first post.</strong> Incomplete pages rank lower in LinkedIn search and immediately signal low investment to visitors. A complete page takes 30 minutes to set up and pays off in every subsequent impression.</li>
          <li><strong>Post native documents over external links.</strong> LinkedIn's algorithm suppresses posts with external links (it wants to keep users on the platform). Native document uploads, video, and text-only posts consistently outperform link shares in organic reach.</li>
          <li><strong>Build an employee advocacy programme.</strong> Ask all employees to follow the Company Page, connect their profile to it as their employer, and reshare at least 2 company posts per month. A 20-person team amplifying company content multiplies reach more than any single content investment.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to every comment within 24 hours.</strong> LinkedIn's algorithm rewards engagement velocity. A post that receives 10 comments in the first 2 hours gets significantly more reach than one that receives 10 comments over 3 days. Prompt responses extend the engagement window.</li>
          <li><strong>Use the analytics to identify your best content, then double down.</strong> If employee spotlights consistently get 3x the engagement of product news, post more spotlights. Data-driven content decisions are more efficient than volume alone.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish a LinkedIn newsletter.</strong> Company Pages can publish newsletters that all followers receive subscription invitations for. Newsletter open rates of 40-50% make this one of the highest-reach organic channels available without paid media.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — posting only promotional content</div>
          <p>Company Pages that post only product announcements, awards, and promotions see minimal engagement and slow follower growth. LinkedIn audiences follow brands for insight and education, not marketing messages. The 80/20 rule applies: 80% educational or industry-relevant content, 20% direct promotion. Brands that invert this ratio see their organic reach erode within months.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common LinkedIn Company Page mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Posting only when there is news:</strong> Sporadic posting — only at product launches or events — means the algorithm deprioritises your page between bursts. Consistent weekly posting maintains algorithmic distribution.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the banner image:</strong> The banner (1128x191px) is prime visual real estate. A blank or generic image misses the opportunity to communicate your value proposition at the top of every profile visit.</li>
          <li><strong>Not encouraging employee follows:</strong> A company with 200 employees but 300 page followers has not activated its internal audience. Every employee follow increases the page's credibility score in LinkedIn's algorithm.</li>
          <li><strong>Forgetting to respond to followers who comment:</strong> Non-responses signal low investment in community and hurt the post's reach metrics. Assign someone to monitor Company Page notifications daily.</li>
          <li><strong>Using the same content strategy for 12+ months without reviewing analytics:</strong> Content preferences shift. Review analytics quarterly and adjust content mix based on what formats and topics are driving follower growth and engagement.</li>
        </ul>

